  <h1>Getting Started</h1>

  <p>
    pdit is an interactive Python editor that displays execution results inline,
    right next to the code that produced them. It's designed for exploratory
    programming, data analysis, and learning Python.
  </p>

  <h2>Installation</h2>

  <p>Install pdit using pip:</p>

  <pre><code>pip install pdit</code></pre>

  <p>Or with uv:</p>

  <pre><code>uv pip install pdit</code></pre>

  <h2>Quick Start</h2>

  <p>Create a Python file and run it with pdit:</p>

  <pre><code># example.py
import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame({'{'}
    'name': ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie'],
    'age': [25, 30, 35]
{'}'})

df</code></pre>

  <pre><code>pdit example.py</code></pre>

  <p>
    This opens your default browser with the pdit interface. Press
    <code>Cmd+Enter</code> (or <code>Ctrl+Enter</code>) to execute the code.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>

  <p>
    pdit parses your Python code into individual statements using Python's AST
    module. Each statement is executed in an IPython kernel, and the results are
    streamed back to the browser in real-time.
  </p>

  <p>Results are grouped by the lines of code that produced them:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Standard output</strong> appears as plain text</li>
    <li><strong>Return values</strong> are displayed with syntax highlighting</li>
    <li><strong>DataFrames</strong> render as scrollable tables</li>
    <li><strong>Plots</strong> appear as inline images</li>
    <li><strong>Errors</strong> are shown with full tracebacks</li>
  </ul>

